  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And after all, continues Ezra, taking up again the אחרי־זאת of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 9:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", - \"after all that is come upon us for our evil deeds, and for our great trespass - yea, Thou our God has spared us more than our iniquity deserved, and hast given us this escaped remnant - can we again break Thy commandments, and join in affinity with the people of these abominations? Wilt Thou not be angry with us even to extirpation, so that no residue and no escaped remnant should be left?\" The premiss in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 9:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is followed in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 9:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " by the conclusion in the form of a question, while the second clause of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 9:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is an explanatory parenthesis. Bertheau construes the passage otherwise. He finds the continuation of the sentence: and after all this ... in the words וגו אתּה כּי, which, calmly spoken, would read: Thou, O God, hast not wholly destroyed us, but hast preserved to us an escaped remnant; while instead of such a continuation we have an exclamation of grateful wonder, emphatically introduced by כּי in the sense of כּי אמנם. With this construction of the clauses, however, no advance is made, and Ezra, in this prayer, does but repeat what he had already said, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 9:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 9:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; although the introductory אהרי leads us to expect a new thought to close the confession. Then, too, the logical connection between the question ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 9:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and what precedes it would be wanting, i.e., a foundation of fact for the question ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 9:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Bertheau remarks on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 9:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that the question: should we return to break (i.e., break again) the commands of God? is an antithesis to the exclamation. But neither does this question, to judge by its matter, stand in contrast to the exclamation, nor is any such contrast indicated by its form. The discourse advances in regular progression only when ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 9:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " forms the conclusion arrived at from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 9:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the thought in the premiss (13a) is limited by the thoughts introduced with כּי. What had come upon Israel for their sins was, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 9:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
